SIMPLE: stave
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stave
<hw>Stave</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧v)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Staff</er>, and corresponding to the pl. <ets>staves</ets>. See
<er>Staff</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of a number of narrow strips
of wood, or narrow iron plates, placed edge to edge to form the sides,
covering, or lining of a vessel or structure; esp., one of the strips
which form the sides of a cask, a pail, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of the cylindrical bars of a lantern wheel; one
of the bars or rounds of a rack, a ladder, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A metrical portion; a stanza; a staff.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us chant a passing <qex>stave</qex>⟦br⟧
In honor of that hero brave.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The five horizontal and parallel
lines on and between which musical notes are written or printed; the
staff{7}.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stave jointer</b></col>, <cd>a machine for dressing the
edges of staves.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stave
<hw>Stave</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Staved</conjf> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧vd)</pr> or <conjf>Stove</conjf>
<pr>(st⟦omac⟧v)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Staving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Stave</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, or <er>Staff</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To break in a stave or the staves of; to break a hole in; to burst;
-- often with <xex>in</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>stave</ex> a cask; to
<ex>stave</ex> in a boat.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To push, as with a staff; -- with
<xex>off</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The condition of a servant <qex>staves</qex> him off to a
distance.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To delay by force or craft; to drive away; --
usually with <xex>off</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>stave</ex> off the execution
of a project</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And answered with such craft as women use,⟦br⟧
Guilty or guiltless, to <qex>stave</qex> off a chance⟦br⟧
That breaks upon them perilously.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To suffer, or cause, to be lost by breaking the
cask.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the wine in the city has been <qex>staved</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To furnish with staves or rundles.</def>
<rj><au>Knolles.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To render impervious or solid by driving with a
calking iron; <as>as, to <ex>stave</ex> lead, or the joints of pipes
into which lead has been run</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To stave and tail</b></col>, <cd>in bear baiting,
(<xex>to stave</xex>) to interpose with the staff, doubtless to stop the
bear; (<xex>to tail</xex>) to hold back the dog by the tail.</cd>
<au>Nares.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stave
<hw>Stave</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To burst in pieces by striking
against something; to dash into fragments.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like a vessel of glass she <qex>stove</qex> and sank.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Staves</ent>⟦br⟧
